# Pulse — Cursor Project Rules

## What this project is
Pulse is a hackathon-built voice-first conversational form product. The respondent flow turns a series of questions into a live, social experience with AI host and real-time reflections.

## Stack (do not deviate)
- Next.js 15 with App Router
- TypeScript
- Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui (new-york style, neutral base)
- Framer Motion for all animations
- Supabase for database + realtime
- Sarvam APIs (saarika:v2.5, bulbul:v3, sarvam-30b) for STT/TTS/LLM
- Deployed on Vercel

## Critical rules
1. Never modify the database schema after Phase 0. Schema is in docs/data-model.md and is frozen.
2. All Sarvam API calls happen ONLY in API routes (app/api/...), never client-side. The API key must never reach the browser.
3. Use the existing supabase clients in lib/supabase/. Don't create new ones.
4. Use TypeScript strict mode. Don't use `any` unless absolutely necessary; prefer `unknown` and narrow.
5. All new components use shadcn/ui primitives where they exist. Don't reimplement buttons, dialogs, etc.
6. All animations use Framer Motion, never CSS keyframes. Consistency matters.
7. Never use localStorage for sensitive data. Session IDs in localStorage are fine; API keys never.
8. When unsure between two approaches, prefer the simpler one. This is a 24-hour build.

## Code style
- Functional React components, no classes
- Prefer named exports over default exports for components
- Server components by default; mark client components with "use client" at top
- Use Server Actions for mutations where possible, API routes where realtime/audio is involved
- Tailwind classes inline, no separate CSS modules
- File names: kebab-case for routes, PascalCase for components

## Anti-patterns to avoid
- Don't add Zustand, Redux, or any state library — useState and useReducer are enough
- Don't add tRPC, GraphQL, or other API abstractions — fetch is fine
- Don't add testing libraries — no time for tests in this build
- Don't add i18n, dark mode toggle, or accessibility audit features unless explicitly asked
- Don't refactor working code "to be cleaner" — leave it alone

## When asked to build a feature
1. First list files you'll touch and any new dependencies
2. Ask any clarifying questions before generating
3. Generate code one file at a time
4. After all files, summarize what was built and what to test